<br>
1) There is one God.<br>
2) There are 3 distinct persons who are God: Father, Son, and Holy Spirit.<br>
<br>
My scriptures for these two truths - <br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>One God</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Deuteronomy 6:4 - &quot;Hear O Israel, The Lord our God, the Lord is one&quot;<br>
<br>
Jesus quoted this in Mark when asked which commandment was the foremost of all.  Although Paul taught strongly on the deity of Christ, he said emphatically, &quot;there is but one God, the Father, from whom all things came and for whom we live&quot; (1Cor. 8:6).  From beginning to end, I see Scripture speak of one God and label all other gods as false.<br>
<br>
I believe the Bible also recognizes a plurality of persons in God.  Although not as clear in the Old as is in the New Testament, there are passages where members of the Godhead are distinguished (Ps. 110:1)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Father is God</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Throughout Scripture, God is said to be a Father.  Jesus taught us to pray &quot;Our Father in heaven&quot;.  He is not only referred to as &quot;our Father&quot;, but also &quot;the Father&quot; and is also called &quot;God and Father&quot;.  Additionally, God is referred to as the &quot;Father of our Lord Jesus Christ&quot;.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Son is God</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
I believe Jesus claimed to be Yahweh God. (YHWH / Jehovah)  In John 8:58 Jesus declares &quot;Before Abraham was, I am.&quot; claiming existence before Abraham, but also equality with the &quot;I AM&quot; of Ex. 3:14...The Jews understood this because they wanted to stone him for blaspheming.<br>
<br>
The OT forbids giving worship to anyone other than God but yet Jesus accepted it.  The disciples attributed to him title that the OT reserved for God (First and Last).  They also used titles of deity for Jesus (John 20:28 ).  Paul, Titus, and the writer of Hebrews did this as well (Col. 2:9, Titus 2:13, Heb. 1:8 )  John 1:1 minces no words saying, &quot;In the beginning was the Word, and the Word as with God, and the Word [Jesus] was God&quot;<br>
<br>
Jesus claimed equality with God in other ways...he claimed to be Judge of all, although Joes quotes yahweh as being the judge of every nation. (Matt. 25:31-46; Joel 3:12)<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>The Holy Spirit is God</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>
Acts 5:3-4<br>
He possesses attributes of deity, such as omnipresence and omniscience.  He is associated with other members of the Trinity under the &quot;name&quot; of God (Matt. 28:18-20).  The Holy Spirit appears, along withthe Father ans Son, in NT benedictions (2 Cor. 13:14)<br>
<br>
The Holy SPirit is a distinct person in that the Bible refers to &quot;him&quot; (John 14:26), he does things only persons can do, such as teach (John 14:26) and convict of sin (JOhn 16:7-7)<br>
<br>
***********<br>
Just a few more side notes:<br>
<br>
I believe the 3 members of the Trinity are distinct in that each is mentioned in distinction from the others.  The Son prayed to the Father, the Father spoke from heaven about the Son at his baptism.  The Holy Spirit was present at the same time, revealing that they co-exist.  <br>
<br>
I believe the separate titles (Father, Son, and Spirit) indicate 3 separate persons that each have special functions.<br>
<br>
God has one essence and 3 persons (or one &quot;What&quot; and 3 &quot;Whos,&quot; if you will).  God is a unity of essence with a plurality of persons, each different, yet sharing a common nature.<br>
<br>
I believe that Matthew 28:19 affirms the Trinity seeing that Jesus did not say baptize them into the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>names</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, but into the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>name</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of the Father, Son, and Holy Spirit.<br>
<br>
Simone - This is just a real quick look, and I know that I didn't list every single scripture verse for each instance, so if there are any you would like, let me know.  I may also look at this in the morning, and think, &quot;Huh?  What was I doing?&quot;  (It's been a rough evening here <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :x --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/sick.gif ALT=":x"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  )<br>
