<br>
The first basis for this argument is that the founder of our church Joseph Smith had a vision at the age of 14 where both the Father and the Son visited him.  Our  scriptures BoM (writings of Prophets on the American Continent from 600 bc to 400 AD) and Pearl of Great Price (writings of Moses and Abraham) back this up.  <br>
<br>
Specifics in the bible include : Acts 7:56  where Stephen before he died saw &quot;the Son of Man (Jesus) standing at the right hand side of God&quot;<br>
<br>
When Christ was baptized, He was standing in the water, the Father was in Heaven and spoke and said how pleased He was with His Son, at the same time the Holy Ghost descended upon Jesus. Three distinct individuals in 3 different places. (Mathew 4:16-17)<br>
<br>
When Christ was in the Garden of Gethsemene, He prayed to his Father.  He said not MY will but THY will be done (two separate people with two separate wills) yet He was willing to bend to the Fathers will knowing why it had to be done.  (Luke 22:42)  In Mathew he went on to clarify how He and the Father are one. (John 17:21) <br>
&quot;That they may all be one, as thou Father art in me and I in thee, that they also may be one in us:...&quot;<br>
<br>
When Jesus was on the Cross, The Father withdrew His presence/spirit from Jesus because Christ had to do it alone. (Mark 15:34) Christ called to Him and asked why He had forsaken Him.<br>
<br>
When Christ taught the people how to pray he taught them to pray to God the Father in His name.  He is the mediator between us and the Father.  He did not teach us to pray to Him.  After He was risen he did accept worship of himself.  LDS do worship Him as our Savior and Redeemer, but we pray to the Father in His name.<br>
<br>
